Locate a Product Code in a Rotated Shelf Index

A warehouse in Coimbatore stores product codes in a sorted array. Due to a system reorganization, the sorted array was rotated at an unknown pivot. The warehouse manager now needs to quickly find the index of a target product code.

Given a rotated sorted array of distinct integers and a target value, return the index of the target if it exists. Otherwise, return -1.

Input format :
The first line contains an integer n — the size of the array
The second line contains n space-separated integers
The third line contains an integer target
Output format :
Print a single integer representing the index of the target
If the target is not present, print -1

Code constraints :
1 <= n <= 5000
-10^4 <= nums[i] <= 10^4
All values in nums are unique
nums is sorted in ascending order before being rotated
-10^4 <= target <= 10^4

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
7
4 5 6 7 0 1 2
0
Output 1 :
4
Input 2 :
7
4 5 6 7 0 1 2
3
Output 2 :
-1

Solution:


// You are using GCC
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    
    vector<int> arr(n);
    
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        cin >> arr[i];
    }
    
    int k;
    cin >> k;
    
    if(k < 0 && k >= n){
        cout<<"-1";
        return 0;
    }
    
    int l = 0;
    int r = n-1;
    
    while(l<=r){
        
        int mid = (r+l)/2;
        
        if(arr[mid] == k){
            cout<<mid;
            return 0;
        }
        else if(arr[l] <= arr[mid]){
            if(arr[l] <= k && k <= arr[mid]){
                r = mid - 1;
            }
            else
            {
                l = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        else if(arr[mid] <= arr[r]){
            if(arr[mid] <= k && k <= arr[r]){
                l = mid + 1;
            }
            else
            {
                r = mid - 1;
            }
        }
       
    }
    
    cout<<"-1";
}
